Clarifying OpenClaw vs Native WSL Performance**\"}]}"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] Great observation — and it makes sense.\n\nYou’re seeing two different workloads:\n\n1) **Windows direct test (`ollama run ...`)**  \n- short prompt  \n- no big conversation history  \n- minimal overhead\n\n2) **Me via OpenClaw session**  \n- much larger prompt (system rules + memory + chat history + tools context)  \n- model routing + gateway overhead  \n- sometimes fallback checks/retries  \n- so Qwen feels slower and heavier here than in raw Ollama CLI\n\nSo Qwen itself may be “fine,” but **its performance inside this agent stack** can still be bad.\n\nHow I’m using it: through OpenClaw’s configured model route (`ollama/...`) from WSL, not the plain Windows CLI path you manually test.\n\nIf you want, I can give you a **read-only 3-command latency comparison** (direct Ollama vs OpenClaw turn) so we measure the gap objectively before deciding keep/remove.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_09c1eed3dfa3a32d0169ba92dbe734819b9f2b836a20454a9e\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.3-codex","usage":{"input":580,"output":315,"cacheRead":38272,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":39167,"cost":{"input":0.001015,"output":0.00441,"cacheRead":0.0066976,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0121226}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773834961450}}
